snippet.textDisplay:
Amazing adventure. This series sailing Greta and father across the Atlantic is fast becoming my favorite. I have deep affection for my home waters. I'm also deeply proud to know you have engaged this mission.

Two observations.

1. Even here on Sailing La Vagabond, I am dismayed to see the sharp uptick in downvotes involved in this journey. Take a stand for something you deeply value, and you learn who your friends are . Predicable, maybe. Still disappointing. For the record, this Yankee New Englander supports your values and your actions 110%.

2. As you learned, the North Atlantic is no joke in the winter. I follow the development and progression of weather systems in the NW Atlantic. I understand the dynamic energy between frigid continental airmasses interacting with the tropical Gulf Stream water, but am still continually astonished how fast and how ferocious the lows become during the winter months. For example, so far this winter I have seen at least several dozen lows deeper than 940 MB riding north-eastward offshore of the states and maritime Canada. In late January I observed data from buoy 44011 (tail of Georges Banks, 170NM ese of Cape Cod) indicating 936mb pressure in sustained 60 knot sw winds...blowing with the Gulf Stream...lucky for any unfortunate seamen in the area. Still, several of these lows have bottomed around 928-930 mb between Newfoundland and Greenland. 60+ knots, frigid freezing sea-spray, with 1000-mile fetch? Thank you. No.

[Edit] The climate model consensus predicts a North Atlantic low between Greenland and Iceland in 7 days (by 19Feb2020) that will reach 921 MB...hurricane category 5 strength. The entire stretch of ocean between Greenland and Iceland will be below 935mb pressure for 5 days! Can't imagine...
